      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "[AI-assisted] Add session history family lookup",
        "body": "## Problem\n\nWhen a threaded conversation has already been split across reset transcripts, `chat.history` and the `sessions_history` tool only read the currently active transcript. The session store can already retain the family through `usageFamilySessionIds`, but history readers do not use that chain and do not discover archived `*.jsonl.reset.<timestamp>` topic transcripts.\n\nThat means an agent/tool can be looking at the correct logical Telegram/Slack/Discord thread and still miss earlier turns after session rollover.\n\n## Fix\n\nAdd an opt-in family history path:\n\n- `chat.history` accepts `includeFamily: true`.\n- `sessions_history` accepts `includeFamily`.\n- `sessions_history` also accepts `resetAncestors` as a tool-facing alias.\n- The gateway resolves `usageFamilySessionIds` in family order, discovers reset archive transcripts in the session store directory by session id prefix, and reads the current active transcript last.\n- Normal `chat.history` behavior remains unchanged: it still reads only the first existing active transcript candidate.\n- `chat.startup` ignores `includeFamily` so UI hydration does not accidentally load ancestor history.\n\n## Validation\n\n- `npm test -- --run packages/gateway-protocol/src/index.test.ts src/agents/openclaw-tools.sessions.test.ts src/gateway/server.chat.gateway-server-chat-b.test.ts`\n  - 3 Vitest shards passed\n  - 141 tests passed\n- `npm run tsgo:test:src`\n  - passed\n- `git diff --check`\n  - passed\n\n## Real Behavior Proof\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** A logical thread whose active session has `usageFamilySessionIds` should be able to fetch earlier reset transcript turns when a caller explicitly requests family history.\n- **Real environment tested:** Local OpenClaw checkout on this PR branch using a temporary session directory and the same reset archive filename pattern that OpenClaw creates for topic transcripts.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n  1. Created a temporary session directory.\n  2. Wrote `ancestor-thread-session-topic-456.jsonl.reset.2026-01-18T04-00-00.000Z` containing `ancestor thread context`.\n  3. Wrote `current-thread-session.jsonl` containing `current thread context`.\n  4. Ran the branch code with `node_modules/.bin/tsx` to parse reset archive timestamps and compare default active-file lookup with family reset-ancestor discovery.\n- **Evidence after fix:** Terminal capture from the local smoke command:\n  ```text\n  $ node_modules/.bin/tsx ./family-history-smoke.ts\n  {\"defaultContainsAncestor\":false,\"familyResetAncestors\":[\"ancestor-thread-session-topic-456.jsonl.reset.2026-01-18T04-00-00.000Z\"],\"activeTranscript\":\"current-thread-session.jsonl\"}\n  ```\n- **Observed result after fix:** The default active transcript lookup stays on `current-thread-session.jsonl`, while family reset-ancestor discovery finds `ancestor-thread-session-topic-456.jsonl.reset.2026-01-18T04-00-00.000Z`. The added gateway RPC test then verifies that `chat.history` excludes that ancestor by default and includes it with `includeFamily: true`.\n- **What was not tested:** I did not run a live Telegram topic end-to-end, and this PR does not add prompt-level carryover summaries or automatic prompt injection. It only adds explicit family history retrieval for gateway/tool callers.\n",
        "branch": "fix/session-history-family",
